Food was not Italian and not good. Flavors were all off. It all tasted like Asian fusion.  Triangolini with corn was not seasoned, no herbs or garlic. It was sickly sweet and tasted like Che Bap (Vietnamese  corn desert pudding). The Bucatini with clams was just so awful. It looked and tasted like Sweet and Sour Chinese noodles, no real sauce just sticky grease covered in raw green onions. We sent it back, it was inedible. The Gemelli should have been an easy win, just plain tomato sauce, but again it was not seasoned and was drowning in raw sliced garlic. I love garlic but this was uncooked and in huge chunks, which again give the dish and odd stirfry flavor. Really disappointing meal. I wouldn't recommend. One Star for competent and attentive staff.

The Tajarin, a lighter, more citrus-focused take on Carbonara, is the visual winner - and while it's VERY good, the Breakfast Sandwich, Orecchiette, and crispy potatoes (side) are absolute MUST try items.. all amazing. Definitely in the top tier of restaurants in all of Brooklyn.  Fausto serves high-end Italian fare with a bistro-like feel.  The pastas are the menu standouts - all of it made from scratch, all of it delicious.  Very nice wine menu and cocktail list.  Service was excellent; attentive without being overbearing.  Would not be surprised if this was awarded a Michelin star soon.

Surprisingly small portions for both appetizers and pasta.  Pricing is aggressive, given the lack of attention to detail.  Arancini were cooked well, with a nice gooey center and a good crunch.  However meatballs were overcooked with a chewy crust from the outside frying for too long.  Duck ragu was well seasoned but overwhelmed the bigoli pasta, to the point it doesn't really read like a pasta dish.  Same with cavatelli with chicken ragu.  Cavatelli were oddly soft.  The ragus were again seasoned well but also were not very distinctive.  And the pricing is confusing.  These are pasta dishes!  They should highlight the pasta, and the pasta should be superb at that price!  A very odd approach.  Drinks were great though!

I've been reading about this place, seeing it on social media... so when we came to NY for a weekend we HAD to come here.  It did not disappoint and far exceeded my expectations, which is kind of hard to do!  We had an 8pm reservation, when we arrived at 7:40, there were several open tables - the hostess informed us that she did in fact have 7:45 reservations coming in, did we mind waiting?  So over to the bar.  The bartender was awesome.  Not that they are hard to make, but she made us an Aperol Spritz and a negroni that were both spot on.  No measuring required.  I've had more than enough bartenders screw up a Spritz that this made me quite happy!  Around our appointed time (It wasn't much past 8pm) we were shown our table.  We were greeted by a extremely friendly and knowledgable waiter.  As I knew I wanted pasta and was a bit overwhelmed at the choices, I asked which was his favorite.  The rabbit he said.  And so our feast began!!!  We started with a couple of appetizers - the sardines which were delicious, the octopus which was cooked perfectly and the pork meatballs with a broccoli rabe pesto.  Yea, I didn't really need the meatballs but someone had gotten them at the bar and I HAD to try them.  If you go, you HAVE to try them!  As per the recommendation, I went with the rabbit bolognese over pasta verde.  Totally blew me away.  I hadn't had rabbit ragu that good since I had it in Tuscany at least 7 years ago.  My husband had the rock shrimp with the black squid ink pasta.  It tasted like the sea.  I will be dreaming of those pastas for a long time!  We did split a main - the chicken with roasted onion.  Its cooked in the wood burning oven so that alone tells you how its going to be!  The wine list here is great - you can also get half bottles, which we did with the cheese course.  Orange wine.  Its all the rage in NY, not so much here in Florida...  Maybe in a few years.  I really enjoyed it.  Again, service is fabulous and when I'm back in the city, you can be sure I'll have my reservation ready at Fausto!
Great place - very good food and great staff.
Great food and cocktails..

Solid mediocre Italian. Portions are ridiculously small. Flavors were good to very good. We had the homemade ricotta and octopus to start. Very tiny portion on the octopus. Good but not wow. I had the bucatini and my bf had the orecchiette...both were good but also on the small side for pasta as a main. Wine list had lots of affordable options and they had a long list of interesting amaros. As for the service it was almost comically overdone. They would come and refill my water or wine after each sip taken (both were left on the table so it was not necessary). Then in between refilling they would ask repeatedly how everything was. It was one step away from the old Belissimo! skit from SNL with Dana Carvey.

Fausto has great seasonal dishes and pastas. This is the perfect place to share plates. I would suggest 2-3 dishes per person. I would suggest trying as many of the pasta dishes as you can, as it’s the highlight of the restaurant. I have tried 5 different pasta dishes and they were all spot on. The Arancini is very good as well as the ceviches that are offered. The meatballs were a bit tough but had nice flavor. I would also recommend any of the seasonal vegetable plates. The salted caramel panna cotta is light and creamy. Very nice experience overall.

I was looking forward to this and brought my folks for mother's day. Unfortunately none of us enjoyed the food and the restaurant, from menu to vibe, has a bit of an identity problem. The flavor profiles were bizarre- a lot of pickled flavors. Small portions. Across the board, from pasta to pork chop, everything was way too salty. I would not call this Italian. Difficult to get by phone and the hostess was very impatient once i did.

I've wanted to check out Fausto since their opening. So when my out of town foodie friend said she'll be around, I thought that would be the beat time to go. We went last night. Firstly, I have to say we had a 530 res, I arrived a few minutes late. She just msg me that she was a little late (MTA woes in NYC). I alerted the hostess. And my friend was nearly an hour late. However, the staff were amazing an so patient with me occupying the table for so long. As I waited the staff were all so attentive. The atmosphere and decor were amazing. When my friend arrived, we had a delicious meal. Everything was perfect. They even moved some things around so we didn't have to rush our meal. Thank you so much for everything Fausto, absolutely perfect. Will definitely come back.

I can't say enough good things about Fausto! It's become the fabulous dining room I've always wanted in my (tiny, Studio) apartment. The staff is so genuinely friendly and helpful. I'm not sure where they were able to find such lovely people. The food is consistently above par and delicious. I can't tell you how many people I have sent over there and I highly recommend everyone check it out (and don't forget to have some of the unbelievable Amaro).

The Torchio might be the best pasta dish I’ve ever eaten.  And I’ve eaten a lot of pasta in my life. I’ve eaten spaghetti. I’ve eaten linguine. I’ve eaten rigatoni. I’ve eaten gnocchi. I’ve eaten tortellini. I’ve eaten ravioli. I’ve eaten gemelli. I’ve eaten elbows. I’ve eaten lasagna. I’ve even had dinosaur shaped pasta.  But that Torchio might be the pasta dish I’ve ever eaten.  Their orchiette is pretty good too.

Fish had good flavors but overcooked. Nothing really hit the mark.  The place was filled to the brim with obnoxious ppl as well, and could barely hear each other without screaming.

The prices are friendly and the ambition is commendable. Service was flawless. I’ve also heard great things about the (extensive) wine list. We did, however, order family style and got all of the (mostly) great food almost 245min later - duck ragú, tortellini, and oriecchetti - came at different temperatures. The duck ragú was way over-salted.  Appetizers were fine but did not leave an impression. Ok the poached egg farrow was actually yummy. The wine, after a lengthy discussion, came fine but did not meet expectations about the hype of the wine list. All said and done - I’ll come back and give it another go.

Easily the best Italian I’ve had maybe ever. The ambiance is great. It’s a great space. Attentive and knowledgeable servers. The food was out of this world. Portions were on the smaller side but an app and 2 main dishes left my boyfriend and me just full enough. The orecchiette and the duck ragu dish were to die for. Highly recommend this place!!
Very good. Exceeded expectations

We had a birthday dinner here and it was fantastic. The team is very welcoming - they got the “come on in” vibe on point. Chicory salad was light fresh and delicious. Cauliflower too. Three pastas all wonderful. Snapper was a standout - something crunchy in it (can’t recall what it was!) but it was so good. And I’m a sucker for the lemon ricotta cake (with a subtle candle). Oh and the wine - they know it well so take their advice. Fausto is a great addition to the neighborhood 👍👍👍

Absolutely incredible pasta. I got the orecchiette and the buckwheat rigatoni and both were exceptional. Service was a tad slow, but they were slammed so it was understandable. Would love to go back and try more of their pastas, but will probably wait until the hype dies down.
In a word:   Amazing!

Just a short train ride from Manhattan and we were in.........ITALY!!  What a joy!  A warm, welcoming and beautiful space with great vibe could only be beat by the best meal we enjoyed since Florence.  We began with Arancini, Red Snapper Crudo and Pork Meatballs.  All outstanding, but save your appetite for the pastas!  Each better than the last.  We were all able to taste quite a few but the best one was the Orecchiette, the Buckwheat Rigatoni, the Whole Wheat Bigoli All Torchio and the Tagliatelle.  Impossible to decide.  I got to try the Striped Bass which was fresh, robustly flavorful as if we were on the Ligurian coast with a great wine from Cinque Terre (follow Joe Campanale's recommendations!!).  Thankfully, we rolled over the finish line with the Lemon Ricotta which was as wonderful as we would expect at this point.  Overall, the food, service and ambiance made for an exceptional experience.  Joe and his team created an awesome Italian hideaway I can't wait to get back to.  I can only imagine if we LIVED in Brooklyn!
Fabulous, personalized and super-well informed bar service. These guys really know their wines. The kitchen is still getting its legs but I'm excited to have Fausto in the neighborhood!

I'm sad to see Franny's go, but so happy it was Fausto to take its place.  Instant stand-out in the neighborhood.  Lots of range in the menu to suit many: I especially liked the shredded chicory, slow poached egg with mushrooms & farro, and tagliatelle w lamb ragu & anchovy.  Pleasant service and cool decor.  I'll definitely be back to try more!
Awesome menu with loads of plates to share and a very good, well-priced wine list. It’s the old Lartusi crew and they really know what they’re doing. Definitely make the trip!

Great new Italian restaurant in Park Slope.  Modern neighborhood feel and upbeat vibe.  Wonderful menu and thoughtful wine list, with attention to great values from Italy.  Food was delicious, full stop.  In particular, we loved the soft boiled egg with mushrooms and Faro, the orecchiette with slow cooked pork, and the lamb chops.  Topped off with excellent service; it was an altogether great first visit.  We'll be back soon.
